    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1970340">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1970340">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1970340)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1970340">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1259135); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1259135&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205776" alt="Hornby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1259135)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1259135); return false;" >Hornby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1392671196 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 Feb 2014 21:06</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1970340">
									

<p>The Federal Bureau of Investigation fills two roles in the United States: it is the federal level criminal investigative service (the function most people think of when they hear &quot;FBI&quot;) and the agency responsible for domestic intelligence operations (primarily but not exclusively counterintelligence and counterespionage). In the latter capacity, it is the only organization within the US intelligence community (IC) specifically tasked with performing operations within the United States and traditionally the only agency in the IC allowed to investigate US citizens in-country (there are a few exceptions to this, but they are rare). Since the PATRIOT Act was passed in 2002, the water has muddied some, but in the vast majority of circumstances domestic intelligence operations are the FBI's bailiwick, rather than, say, the CIA's. It is worth noting that the United States IC is downright Byzantine in its bureaucratic organization, and very few countries have organized their ICs in the same way.</p>
<p>To determine the British (or for that matter any other country's) counterpart to the UIU, it becomes necessary to consider two things: first, is the UIU part of the FBI's law enforcement capacity or its intelligence capacity; second, where would the other country's government have a comparable unit (law enforcement, military, intelligence, independent organization, etc.)? If we assume the UK organizes its governmental capacity to handle the paranormal in the same manner as the United States, then their counterpart to the UIU would be either part of the Security Service (what most people refer to as MI5 - this organization is the domestic intelligence agency for the UK) or part of the British police force (I'd guess probably a wing of the Metropolitan Police Service, but someone with more familiarity about the UK's police structure would be better able to answer that than I). However, I doubt the UK's counterpart agency would be specifically subordinated to either, rather being an independent organization in service to the Crown.</p>

							</div>

								
					
