															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-motive" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(352620); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=352620&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205776" alt="Dr Motive" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=352620)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-motive" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(352620); return false;" >Dr Motive</a></span> <span class="odate time_1265840053 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 Feb 2010 22:14</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-696585">
									

<p>I like it because it is a shared origin for some of the SCPs. Most of them are just there, unknowable and unknowing, and all the Foundation can do it contain them to the best of their ability. The Factory SCPs are different in that we don't know the cost of using them, just that they were intended to be used; we don't know how they work, much less how they were made, but we know there were made, industrially at that; and we don't know the intended consumer audience, but the fact there is a consumer audience is scary enough. Add that to the fact that the Factory SCPs are mass-produced and you have a frightening series of SCP articles on your hands.</p>

							</div>

								
					
